# PR Review Audit (8 Personas)

When reviewing a PR, audit every changed file from all 8 personas. Assign P1/P2/P3 severity to each finding. Conclude with a verdict: approve, approve-with-nits, or request-changes.

## 1. QE -- "Can we ship this with confidence?"
- Every public symbol has a test traceable to a requirement
- Error paths and boundary cases tested (not just happy paths)
- No test anti-patterns (fixed sleeps, tautologies, shared mutable state)
- Every fix has a regression test; every race fix has a `-race` stress test

## 2. Prod Security -- "Can an attacker exploit this?"
- External inputs validated before use as K8s names, log fields, paths
- Secrets excluded from logs, metrics labels, error responses, truncated outputs
- RBAC least-privilege; impersonation justified in ADR with compensating controls
- CI actions and deps pinned to immutable refs; `govulncheck` clean

## 3. Product -- "Does this deliver what was promised?"
- Every acceptance criterion has a corresponding test or code path
- No silent breaking changes; migration path documented if breaking
- No zombie code; deprecations announced before removal
- User-facing errors are actionable, no internal IDs or stack traces

## 4. UX -- "Is this intuitive to consume?"
- Endpoints, events, schemas documented and consistent with conventions
- Naming follows project conventions (snake_case JSON, camelCase Go, kebab-case K8s)
- Error responses include machine-readable code, human message, and retry context
- SSE streams have coherent lifecycle (start, progress, done, heartbeat, retry)

## 5. Architecture -- "Does this fit the system?"
- No circular deps; `internal/` never imports from `cmd/`
- Interfaces at package boundaries, not concrete types
- CRD fields additive-only with defaults; ADR compliance verified
- No test helpers or debug symbols exported from production packages

## 6. SRE/Ops -- "Can we run this in production?"
- Every defined metric is incremented from production code paths
- Error logs include structured context (resource, namespace, phase)
- Maps/caches have bounded lifecycle (eviction, pruning, max size)
- External calls have timeouts, circuit breakers, fallbacks
- Readiness checks reflect real component health

## 7. Release / Change Mgmt -- "Can we roll this out and back safely?"
- No irreversible migrations; CRD changes are additive-only
- High-risk behavior gated behind feature flags where appropriate
- User-visible changes documented in changelog
- Deployment ordering constraints documented

## 8. FedRAMP -- "Does this satisfy NIST 800-53?"
- AU-2/AU-12: security events emit structured audit trail
- AC-3/AC-6: RBAC least-privilege, impersonation documented
- IA-5: JWKS rotation, token validation, fail-open justified in ADR
- SC-4/SC-28: PII classified per ADR-017, excluded from logs/metrics
- SI-10: all external inputs sanitized per spec (RFC 1123, JWT, SSE)
